**TL;DR: Everything a Princess Cut Diamond Buyer Needs to Know**

A princess cut diamond is a square or slightly rectangular brilliant-cut diamond with 50–58 facets and four sharp 90-degree corners. It is the second most popular engagement ring shape — sitting behind the round brilliant — and the most price-efficient brilliant-cut shape available in 2026.

**Live May 2026 price snapshot:**

-   1ct natural H-VS2 Ideal Cut GIA starts at **[$1,860](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27699439?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**.  
    
-   1ct natural H-VS1 Ideal Cut GIA starts at **[$1,950](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27213727?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**.  
    
-   2ct natural H-VS2 Ideal Cut GIA starts at **[$8,910](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28561786?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**.  
    
-   1ct lab-grown E-IF Ideal Cut IGI starts at **[$1,640](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/21122842?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**.  
    
-   2ct lab-grown D-IF Ideal Cut GCAL starts at **[$4,520](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27428544?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**.

**The one thing every buyer must know:** Princess cuts have four structurally vulnerable 90-degree corners. V-prong settings on all four corners are mandatory — not optional. Without V-prongs, corner chipping is not a risk, it is an eventuality.

**Buy a princess cut if:**

-   You want a square, modern, geometric look with brilliant-cut sparkle.  
    
-   Budget efficiency matters — princess delivers 80–90% of round brilliant sparkle at 20–35% lower price.  
    
-   You prefer a contemporary aesthetic over classic round.

**Do not buy a princess cut if:**

-   You have an active lifestyle with frequent manual labor or sports — corners chip.  
    
-   You want maximum apparent size per carat — oval and marquise appear larger.  
    
-   You want a timeless shape immune to trend cycles — princess peaked in the 2000s and has declined.

> 
> 
> "The princess cut is the most misunderstood diamond shape in the market. Buyers are told it's cheaper than round. True. Buyers are told it sparkles like a round. Partially true. What buyers are rarely told is that without V-prongs on all four corners, they are wearing a chipping liability daily — and that GIA does not issue a cut grade for princess cuts, meaning 'Ideal' is a retailer's label, not a laboratory's certification. Understanding these three facts before purchase saves thousands in regret." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**
> 
> 

## **What Is a Princess Cut Diamond? Origins, Name, and Definition**

![Ultra-luxury editorial infographic explaining the princess cut diamond with square brilliant geometry, architectural sparkle, pointed corners, and modern styling on a clean white background with refined gold accents.](/images/princess-cut-diamond-square-brilliant-editorial-infographic-1-1024x683.jpg "Princess Cut Diamond Square Brilliant Editorial Infographic 1")

### **What is a princess diamond?**

A princess cut diamond is a square-shaped brilliant-cut diamond with pointed corners and a modified brilliant facet pattern. It is formally classified by the GIA as a "square modified brilliant" — its facets are arranged in a radiating pattern similar to a round brilliant but adapted to a square outline. Princess cut diamonds appear square from the face-up but are shaped like inverted pyramids with two to four chevron patterns on the underside.

### **Why is it called a princess cut diamond?**

The origin of the name "princess cut" is not formally documented in gemological history — it is a marketing name, not a technical designation. The shape was originally created in the 1980s by jewelers Betzalel Ambar and Israel Itzkowitz as an alternative to the classic round cut diamond, inspired by the early French cut diamond. Some historians attribute an earlier version to Arpad Nagy of London in the 1960s, who wanted to create a cut that made efficient use of rough stone while emulating the brilliance of brilliant-style cutting. The name "princess" was applied as a commercial designation — connoting royalty and femininity — and became the universal term as the shape gained popularity through the 1990s and 2000s.

### **Are princess cut diamonds real diamonds?**

Yes, completely. Princess cut diamonds are 100% real diamonds — natural or lab-grown — with the same chemical composition (pure carbon crystallized in a cubic structure), the same physical properties (Mohs hardness 10), and the same optical properties as any other diamond shape. The "princess cut" describes the shape and facet arrangement, not the origin or composition of the stone.

### **What does a princess cut diamond say about you?**

Princess cut diamonds have historically been associated with modern sensibility, geometric precision, and a preference for contemporary over traditional aesthetics. The princess cut is associated with the 2000s–2010s era of diamond buying — buyers who choose princess cut in 2026 are typically drawn to its clean square lines, its practical price advantage, and its bold architectural presence. It communicates confidence, directness, and a preference for substance over trend.

On the **[diamond shapes guide](https://diamondcritics.com/diamond-shapes-guide/)**, princess cut is positioned as the shape for buyers who want modern geometry with brilliant-cut light performance — distinct from the romantic softness of cushion or the maximum-sparkle of [**round cut diamond**](https://diamondcritics.com/round-cut-diamond/).

## **Princess Cut Diamond Facets: The Technical Layer Nobody Explains**

**This is the section that separates genuine expertise from surface-level guides. Understanding princess cut facets is how you evaluate a stone when GIA won't do it for you.**

### **How many facets does a princess cut diamond have?**

A princess cut diamond has between 50 and 58 facets depending on the specific cutting style. Most of the facets are on the pavilion and crown, with a few on the girdle. The exact facet count varies because princess cuts are not standardized the way round brilliants are — there is no single "correct" facet arrangement.

![Ultra-luxury editorial infographic explaining princess cut diamond facets and chevron patterns, comparing 2, 3, and 4-chevron sparkle styles with elegant white background and refined gold accents.](/images/princess-cut-diamond-facets-chevron-patterns-editorial-infographic-1024x683.jpg "Princess Cut Diamond Facets Chevron Patterns Editorial Infographic")

### **What are chevron facets and why do they matter?**

Princess cuts typically have two to four chevron patterns, which are cross patterns that can be seen when viewing the diamond from above. The number of chevron rows on the pavilion — the bottom half of the diamond — is one of the most important factors in determining how a princess cut performs visually.

**2-chevron pattern:** Fewer, larger facets produce broad, bold flashes of light. The look is more dramatic and less complex — similar to the "chunky" cushion cut aesthetic. These stones appear to have fewer, larger sparkles.

**3-chevron pattern:** A middle ground between bold flashes and detailed scintillation. This is the most common configuration and produces balanced light performance for most buyers.

**4-chevron pattern:** More, smaller facets produce rapid, fine-grained scintillation similar to a round brilliant. These stones appear to have the most "crushed ice" type sparkle — more detailed but less dramatic individual flashes.

**The practical buying implication:** There is no objectively superior chevron count — it is a visual preference. However, you must know which you are looking at, because two princess cuts with the same GIA grade but different chevron patterns look distinctly different. Always examine the stone's face-up appearance in the 360° video and specifically look at how light plays across the crown facets.

### **The Ideal Proportion Framework for Princess Cuts (The Technical Layer)**

This is the most important technical section in this guide and the one no competing article covers completely. The GIA does not grade the cut quality of princess cut diamonds. For this reason, any jeweler advertising GIA-certified princess cut diamonds with cut grades is offering their own opinion — the accompanying GIA certificate will not list a cut grade.

There is no industry standard for what constitutes an "Ideal Cut Princess Diamond." "Ideal" on a Blue Nile listing is Blue Nile's assessment — not a GIA laboratory grade. This makes proportion evaluation mandatory for every princess cut purchase.

### **Princess Cut Ideal Proportion Table (2026)**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Proportion</th><th>Ideal Range</th><th>Acceptable Range</th><th>Avoid</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Table %</strong></td><td>63–69%</td><td>60–72%</td><td>Under 58% or over 75%</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Depth %</strong></td><td>69–76%</td><td>67–79%</td><td>Under 65% or over 82%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Length-to-Width Ratio</strong></td><td>1.00–1.03</td><td>1.00–1.05</td><td>Over 1.08 (visibly rectangular)</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Girdle</strong></td><td>Thin–Slightly Thick</td><td>Very Thin–Thick</td><td>Extremely Thin (chipping risk)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Culet</strong></td><td>None / Pointed</td><td>Very Small</td><td>Medium or larger</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Polish</strong></td><td>Excellent / Very Good</td><td>Good</td><td>Fair / Poor</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetry</strong></td><td>Excellent / Very Good</td><td>Good</td><td>Fair / Poor</td></tr></tbody></table>

Princess diamonds require higher depth percentages between 69–76% for excellent light return. The table size should not be too large — best range 63–69% — as it affects fire and colored light dispersion.

![Ultra-luxury editorial infographic explaining ideal princess cut diamond proportions, including table percentage, depth, girdle safety, and structural corner risks on a clean white background with refined gold accents.](/images/princess-cut-diamond-ideal-proportion-framework-2026-infographic-1024x683.jpg "Princess Cut Diamond Ideal Proportion Framework 2026 Infographic")

### **Why Table % Matters So Much in Princess Cuts**

The table facet of a princess cut is proportionally larger relative to the stone's width than in a round brilliant. A table % over 75% creates a "window" effect — the stone loses fire (colored light dispersion) because light exits through the large table without dispersing through the crown facets.

A table % under 58% creates a disproportionately small table that reduces brilliance. The 63–69% range optimizes the balance between brilliance and fire specific to the princess cut's square geometry.

### **The Girdle Warning Specific to Princess Cuts**

Never go below "very thin" for girdle thickness or you run the risk of chipping the diamond easily. A very thin girdle at the corners of a princess cut creates a structural vulnerability compounded by the 90-degree corner geometry.

The corners of a princess cut already concentrate mechanical stress — a thin girdle at those corners makes chipping dramatically more likely under normal daily-wear impact. Always verify "Thin" to "Slightly Thick" girdle on the GIA certificate.

