=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$14,300</a></strong></td><td><strong>7/10 — Market Average.</strong> A standard price for this grade. Good reliability, but not as much "value" as the H-VS1 options in the same range.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td>2.24ct</td><td>H-VS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28413138?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$14,460</a></strong></td><td><strong>10/10 — The Carat Hunter.</strong> For just a few hundred more, you jump to 2.24ct. This is the best "size-to-dollar" ratio in the upper half of this list.</td></tr><tr><td>2.02ct</td><td>G-VS1 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28653601?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$14,610</a></strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — The Peak Choice.</strong> The most expensive for a reason. Likely represents a "Super Ideal" cut with perfect light performance scores.</td></tr></tbody></table>

**Critical 2ct data insight:** The 2.05ct H-VS2 at $8,910 versus the 2.00ct H-VS2 at $11,790 — a $2,880 gap for 0.05ct more diamond at lower price.

This is the "magic size" phenomenon: the 2.05ct stone exceeds the 2ct psychological threshold (buyers search specifically for "2 carat") but costs significantly less because it falls slightly outside the round-number premium. This is genuine market inefficiency buyers can exploit.

### **3ct+ Natural Princess Cut — The Collector Tier**

