al</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/15595103?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$33,180</a></strong></td><td><strong>8/10 — Stability Play.</strong> A slightly higher premium for a 3ct stone, usually indicating better symmetry or "None" fluorescence on the GIA report.</td></tr><tr><td>3.01ct</td><td>G-VS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28847395?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$33,790</a></strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — The G-Color Sweet Spot.</strong> This is the professional's favorite combo: G color looks colorless to 99% of people, and VS2 provides great value.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td>2.50ct</td><td>F-VVS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26044557?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$34,240</a></strong></td><td><strong>10/10 for Purity.</strong> If you prioritize clarity over absolute size, this VVS2 is "loupe clean." It will have a mirror-like finish internally.</td></tr><tr><td>3.04ct</td><td>H-VS1 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28662809?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$35,350</a></strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — Solid Performance.</strong> A robust 3ct VS1. This stone is for the buyer who wants zero anxiety about seeing an inclusion.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td>3.20ct</td><td>H-VVS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28401914?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$36,390</a></strong></td><td><strong>10/10 — The Carat Jumper.</strong> Moving from 3.0 to 3.2ct is a visible jump on the finger. This is a very fair price for VVS quality at this weight.</td></tr><tr><td>3.01ct</td><td>H-VS1 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29007584?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$38,590</a></strong></td><td><strong>8/10 — Premium Median.</strong> Priced higher than earlier 3ct H-VS1s, likely due to a more recent listing or a "perfect" table/depth ratio (60/60).</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td>3.01ct</td><td>E-VS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28056197?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$39,400</a></strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — The Colorless Peak.</strong> At the "E" color grade, the diamond is ice-white. This is for those who want a 3ct showstopper with elite color.</td></tr><tr><td>3.07ct</td><td>H-VS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/16432886?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$40,070</a></strong></td><td><strong>7/10 — Diminishing Returns.</strong> We've crossed the $40k mark for H-VS2. Only recommended if the cut scores are in the top 1% of GIA results.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td>3.04ct</td><td>G-VS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/17324522?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$41,110</a></strong></td><td><strong>8/10 — G-Color Stability.</strong> A consistent price for a high-quality G-color. Secure, beautiful, and standard.</td></tr><tr><td>3.07ct</td><td>G-VS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/17454685?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$44,670</a></strong></td><td><strong>7/10 — The Brand Tax.</strong> This higher price for the same spec usually indicates an older inventory item or a specialized vendor markup.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td>3.01ct</td><td>H-VS1 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/123198?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$45,320</a></strong></td><td><strong>7/10 — Overpriced.</strong> For $45k, we should be looking at F or E colors. This H-color carries a significant premium.</td></tr><tr><td>3.53ct</td><td>G-IF Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28075445?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$48,190</a></strong></td><td><strong>10/10 — The Rarity Winner.</strong> 3.5 carats AND Internally Flawless. This is a collector-grade stone at a surprisingly aggressive sub-$50k price.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td>3.01ct</td><td>E-VVS1 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28657615?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$59,420</a></strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — The Perfectionist’s Choice.</strong> E-color combined with VVS1 means this diamond is technically superior to 99.9% of stones on the market.</td></tr><tr><td>3.30ct</td><td>F-VS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/16490771?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$68,360</a></strong></td><td><strong>8/10 — Large Colorless Play.</strong> An expensive step up, but for the 3.3ct weight, the "F" color ensures it looks absolutely white from every angle.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td>4.10ct</td><td>H-VS2 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/14103561?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&